metadata.title: Beechcraft Super King Air
aws::graph::propositions: # Beechcraft Super King Air Military and Government Operations
The Japan Ground Self-Defense Force operates nine B300s.
The B300s operated by Japan Ground Self-Defense Force are designated LR-2.
The Japan Ground Self-Defense Force uses B300s in the reconnaissance role.
The Japan Ground Self-Defense Force uses B300s in the communications role.
The B300s were delivered to the Japan Ground Self-Defense Force between 1998 and 2004.
The B300s delivered to Japan Ground Self-Defense Force include the last B300 built without the Pro Line 21 avionics package.
The last B300 built without the Pro Line 21 avionics package has the construction number FL-382.
The Royal Bahamas Defence Force operates a single B300.
The Royal Bahamas Defence Force uses its B300 for maritime patrol duties.
The Royal Bahamas Defence Force uses its B300 for reconnaissance duties.
Beechcraft announced on March 6, 2007 that the Iraqi Air Force had ordered five King Air 350ERs.
The King Air 350ERs ordered by the Iraqi Air Force were scheduled for delivery commencing late in 2007.
Hawker Beechcraft exhibited a King Air 350ER at the 2007 Paris Air Show.
Hawker Beechcraft exhibited a King Air 350ER at the Royal International Air Tattoo in 2007.
The Royal International Air Tattoo occurred the month following the 2007 Paris Air Show.

text:
32 Squadron and No. 38 Squadron.
The Japan Ground Self-Defense Force operates nine B300s, designated LR-2, in the reconnaissance and communications roles. The aircraft were delivered between 1998 and 2004 and include the last B300 built without the Pro Line 21 avionics package (c/no. FL-382).
The Royal Bahamas Defence Force operates a single B300 on maritime patrol and reconnaissance duties.
Beechcraft announced on March 6, 2007 that the Iraqi Air Force had ordered five King Air 350ERs for delivery commencing late in 2007. Hawker Beechcraft exhibited a King Air 350ER at the 2007 Paris Air Show; and at the Royal International Air Tattoo the following month.
